President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation recognizing October 6th as German-American Day. He pays tribute to the millions of Americans of German ancestry who have contributed to the country's progress and prosperity. The proclamation acknowledges the arrival of 13 German families in Pennsylvania in 1683, marking the beginning of a chapter in American history influenced by Germans. It highlights the contributions of German Americans in various sectors, emphasizing their role as leaders and innovators. The proclamation also emphasizes the strong ties between Germany and the United States, as well as their shared values and vision for a better world. President Obama encourages all Americans to learn about the history of German Americans and reflect on their contributions to the nation.